    famousFor: 'Cape Reinga, Treaty of Waitangi, Kauri trees',
    story: `Kaia had never planned to travel the entire length of New Zealand. She had also never planned to be accompanied by a talking kiwi bird with an attitude problem. But here she was, standing at the very top of the North Island in Northland — known in te reo Māori as Te Tai Tokerau — with a small, round, feathery companion named Biscuit perched on her backpack.\n\n"Are we there yet?" Biscuit asked, even though they had only just arrived.\n\n"We literally JUST got here," Kaia said, staring out at the spectacular view from Cape Reinga, where the Tasman Sea and the Pacific Ocean crash into each other in a swirl of wild, churning water. According to Māori legend, this is the place where spirits depart Aotearoa on their journey to the afterlife. Kaia thought it was both beautiful and a little bit spooky.\n\n"Well, I don't like it," Biscuit announced. "Too much wind. My feathers are going all wonky."\n\nKaia rolled her eyes. She had found Biscuit that morning in her garden in Auckland, sitting on a feijoa and complaining about the quality of the worms in her lawn. When she had — very reasonably — screamed at the sight of a talking bird, Biscuit had looked deeply offended and said, "Rude. I was about to compliment your garden."\n\nSomehow, within an hour, Biscuit had convinced Kaia that the two of them needed to travel through all sixteen regions of New Zealand. "It'll be educational!" he had insisted. "And I need snacks from every region. It's for science."\n\nSo here they were in Northland, the northernmost region, home to stunning beaches, ancient forests, and the town of Whangārei, which is the region's largest city.\n\n"Right," said Kaia, pulling out her travel notebook. "Northland. First stop on our adventure. What should we see?"\n\n"Snacks," said Biscuit immediately.\n\n"Besides snacks."\n\nBiscuit huffed. "Fine. I suppose we could look at some of those enormous kauri trees everyone goes on about. Apparently, Tāne Mahuta in the Waipoua Forest is the largest living kauri tree in New Zealand. It's estimated to be between 1,250 and 2,500 years old."\n\nKaia's eyes went wide. "Two THOUSAND?"\n\n"I know, right? That tree was growing before some of the most famous civilisations in history even got started. Makes you feel a bit small, doesn't it?" Biscuit paused. "Well, it makes ME feel small. You're already enormous compared to me, so you probably feel small all the time. Wait, that doesn't work. Forget I said anything."\n\nThey made their way to Waipoua Forest, and when Kaia saw Tāne Mahuta, she actually gasped. The tree was MASSIVE — over 50 metres tall, with a trunk so wide that if Kaia lay down head to toe around it, she'd need about fifteen of herself to circle it. Its bark was grey and rugged, and its canopy spread out like a giant green umbrella.\n\n"I feel like I should bow," Kaia whispered.\n\n"I feel like I should climb it," said Biscuit.\n\n"You can't fly, and you definitely can't climb."\n\n"I have hidden talents!" Biscuit said, then immediately tripped over a tree root and rolled into a fern. "That was on purpose," he said from somewhere inside the foliage.\n\nAfter rescuing Biscuit from the fern (he had somehow gotten tangled in it like a small, angry ball of yarn), they headed to the town of Paihia in the Bay of Islands. Paihia is a popular tourist spot, and it sits right near Waitangi, one of the most important historical sites in all of New Zealand.\n\n"This is where the Treaty of Waitangi was signed in 1840," Kaia read from a sign at the Waitangi Treaty Grounds. "It's the founding document of New Zealand — an agreement between Māori chiefs and the British Crown."\n\n"Incredibly important," Biscuit agreed solemnly. Then he spotted the gift shop. "Ooh! Do they sell biscuits in there? It seems only fair, given my name."\n\nThe Treaty Grounds were beautiful — there was a large carved meeting house called Te Whare Rūnanga, and a massive waka (war canoe) called Ngātokimatawhaorua that was over 35 metres long. Kaia tried to imagine dozens of warriors paddling it across the bay and got goosebumps.\n\n"That waka is longer than a bus," she said.\n\n"I get seasick on buses," Biscuit said. "And boats. And honestly, I once got carsick while standing still, so I'm not the best judge of transportation."\n\nThey explored Kerikeri next, a lovely town famous for being one of the earliest places where Māori and European settlers lived together. Kaia saw the Stone Store, which is the oldest stone building in New Zealand, built in 1836.\n\n"Imagine all the biscuits that have been stored in the Stone Store," Biscuit said dreamily.\n\n"It wasn't for biscuits. It was a trading post."\n\n"Trading... biscuits?"\n\n"No."\n\nBiscuit looked genuinely heartbroken.\n\nAs the afternoon light turned golden, they stopped at one of Northland's gorgeous beaches. The region has some of the warmest weather in New Zealand, and the sand was the colour of honey.\n\n"Fun fact," Kaia said, reading her guidebook. "Ninety Mile Beach up here is actually only about 55 miles long. Someone got the name wrong and it just stuck."\n\n"That's the most relatable thing I've ever heard," said Biscuit. "I once told everyone my name was Sir Biscuit von Featherbottom III for a whole month and nobody questioned it."\n\n"Did you just make that up?"\n\n"Maybe. Maybe not. You'll never know." Biscuit shook his feathers dramatically. "So where are we going next?"\n\nKaia looked at the map. South. Towards the biggest city in New Zealand. "Auckland," she said with a grin. "Tāmaki Makaurau."\n\n"Excellent," said Biscuit, already waddling south. "I've heard great things about the snack situation in Auckland. Onward!"\n\nAnd so, with the sun setting behind the ancient kauri forests of Northland, Kaia and Biscuit began their journey south to Auckland, the City of Sails. Kaia had a feeling this was going to be the adventure of a lifetime.\n\nBiscuit had a feeling he was going to need a bigger backpack. For snacks.`,
