    famousFor: 'Sky Tower, volcanoes, harbour',
    story: `Auckland. Tāmaki Makaurau. The City of Sails. The Big Smoke. Whatever you wanted to call it, it was BIG. Kaia had been to Auckland before — she actually lived nearby — but seeing it through Biscuit's eyes made everything feel brand new.\n\n"WHAT IS THAT GIANT NEEDLE THING?" Biscuit shrieked as soon as they arrived in the city centre, staring up at the Sky Tower with his tiny beak hanging open.\n\n"That's the Sky Tower," Kaia said proudly. "It's 328 metres tall. One of the tallest towers in the Southern Hemisphere."\n\n"Why would anyone BUILD something that tall? What if it falls over? What if there's an earthquake? What if a very large bird lands on top and tips it?" Biscuit was waddling in panicked circles.\n\n"First of all, it's designed to withstand earthquakes. Second, what very large bird are you worried about?"\n\n"I don't know! A really big seagull? You don't know what seagulls are planning, Kaia. They have SCHEMES."\n\nDespite his fear of heights (which, Kaia kept reminding him, was very strange for a bird), Biscuit reluctantly agreed to go up the Sky Tower. They took the lift, and as it zoomed upward, Biscuit pressed himself flat against the floor like a feathery pancake.\n\n"I can feel my organs rearranging," he moaned.\n\n"That's not how lifts work."\n\n"My organs disagree."\n\nBut when they reached the observation deck and looked out, even Biscuit was speechless. For about three seconds.\n\n"Okay, FINE, this is amazing," he admitted. Auckland stretched out in every direction — a glittering city built across a narrow strip of land between two harbours. The Waitematā Harbour sparkled to the east, and the Manukau Harbour gleamed to the west. Hundreds of sailboats dotted the water, which is why Auckland is called the City of Sails.\n\n"You can see the volcanic cones from here," Kaia pointed out. And she was right — Auckland is built on a volcanic field of about 53 volcanoes. Don't panic though — most of them have been sleeping for thousands of years.\n\n"FIFTY-THREE VOLCANOES?" Biscuit yelped. "And people just LIVE here? On purpose? With VOLCANOES underneath them?"\n\n"They're mostly extinct or dormant."\n\n"MOSTLY?!"\n\n"Biscuit, calm down. The last eruption was Rangitoto about 600 years ago."\n\nBiscuit eyed Rangitoto Island through the window. It sat in the Hauraki Gulf looking peaceful and green, like a giant turtle shell rising from the sea. It was actually Auckland's youngest and largest volcano, and its distinctive shape was visible from almost everywhere in the city.\n\n"It LOOKS innocent," Biscuit muttered. "That's exactly what a volcano WANTS you to think."\n\nAfter surviving the Sky Tower (Biscuit insisted on a certificate of bravery, which Kaia drew on a napkin), they took a ferry across to Rangitoto Island itself. The walk to the summit took about an hour, through crunchy black lava fields and pōhutukawa forests.\n\n"My legs are the size of matchsticks, Kaia," Biscuit panted as they climbed. "This is a human-sized walk. I am not human-sized. I am kiwi-sized. Which is MUCH smaller."\n\nKaia scooped him up and plopped him on her backpack. "Better?"\n\n"Infinitely. Carry on, my noble steed."\n\nThe view from the top of Rangitoto was worth every step. They could see the whole of Auckland's harbour, the other volcanic islands, and the city skyline with the Sky Tower poking up like a needle.\n\n"Auckland has about 1.7 million people," Kaia said. "It's the biggest city in New Zealand by far. About a third of the whole country lives here."\n\n"That's a LOT of people who chose to live on top of volcanoes," Biscuit said, shaking his head. "Brave. Foolish. Bravely foolish."\n\nBack on the mainland, they explored the Auckland waterfront at Viaduct Harbour, where fancy yachts bobbed in the water and restaurants lined the boardwalk. Auckland has hosted the America's Cup yacht race multiple times, and you could practically smell the sailing heritage in the salty air.\n\n"Auckland is also incredibly diverse," Kaia told Biscuit as they walked through the bustling streets. "People from all over the world live here. You can find food from practically every country."\n\n"EVERY country?" Biscuit's eyes lit up. "Do any of those countries specialise in biscuits?"\n\n"Basically all of them."\n\n"This is the greatest city on Earth."\n\nThey stopped at Mount Eden — or Maungawhau, one of Auckland's most famous volcanic cones. The crater at the top is a perfect grassy bowl, and the 360-degree views of the city are spectacular. It's a sacred site for local Māori iwi (tribes), so visitors are asked to stay on the paths and treat it with respect.\n\n"It's like a giant salad bowl," Biscuit observed, peering into the crater.\n\n"Please don't compare a sacred volcanic crater to a salad bowl."\n\n"A sacred salad bowl?"\n\nKaia gave him The Look. Biscuit had only known Kaia for two days, but he had already learned to fear The Look.\n\n"Moving on!" he said quickly.\n\nAs the sun began to set, painting Auckland's harbour in shades of orange and pink, Kaia and Biscuit sat on the waterfront eating fish and chips (well, Kaia ate fish and chips — Biscuit ate a worm he found near a bench, which he described as "vintage" and "earthy with notes of mud").\n\n"Auckland fun fact," Kaia said. "The Māori name Tāmaki Makaurau means 'Tāmaki desired by many.' Heaps of iwi wanted to live here because of the rich land and two harbours. It was basically the most popular place in the country even hundreds of years ago."\n\n"I can see why," Biscuit said. "Excellent worms. Very cosmopolitan."\n\nKaia laughed and pulled out her map. Their next destination was south — to the Waikato region, home to rolling green farmland, mysterious underground caves, and a certain movie set that Kaia was VERY excited about.\n\n"Next stop: Waikato," she announced.\n\n"What's in Waikato?"\n\n"Hobbiton."\n\nBiscuit stared at her. "You mean... little round doors? Hobbit holes? SECOND BREAKFAST?"\n\n"You've seen the movies?!"\n\n"Kaia, I am a talking kiwi bird. My life is already fantasy. Of COURSE I've seen the movies." He hopped to his feet. "What are we waiting for? TO THE SHIRE!"\n\nAnd with that, they headed south towards the green hills of the Waikato, leaving Auckland's glittering skyline behind them.`,
