    famousFor: 'Hobbiton, Waitomo Caves, dairy farming, longest river',
    story: `The Waikato region is GREEN. Not just normal green — the kind of green that makes you wonder if someone has turned up the colour saturation on reality. Rolling hills, lush farmland, and more cows than Kaia could count stretched out in every direction.\n\n"That's because Waikato is the dairy capital of New Zealand," Kaia explained as they drove through the countryside. "There are literally millions of cows here."\n\nBiscuit, who was sitting on the dashboard (against all safety regulations), pressed his beak against the window. "I've never seen so many cows. This is either wonderful or terrifying. I can't decide."\n\n"Why would it be terrifying?"\n\n"Have you ever been stared at by a cow, Kaia? Really STARED at? They know things. They're plotting something."\n\n"You said the same thing about seagulls."\n\n"EVERYTHING IS PLOTTING SOMETHING. I'm the only honest creature in this country."\n\nTheir first stop was Hobbiton, the famous movie set near the town of Matamata. When Peter Jackson was filming The Lord of the Rings and The Hobbit trilogies, he found these perfect rolling green hills and built an entire hobbit village on them. And unlike most movie sets, this one was kept standing permanently, so visitors can walk through the Shire in real life.\n\nKaia practically vibrated with excitement as they walked through the gate. "Look! The hobbit holes! The Party Tree! Bag End!"\n\nBiscuit waddled alongside her, his eyes as round as buttons. The tiny round doors built into the hillside were painted cheerful colours — green, yellow, blue — with little gardens and mailboxes and washing lines in front of them.\n\n"These doors are MY size!" Biscuit gasped. "Finally! Architecture for the vertically challenged!" He posed in front of a bright green hobbit hole door and tried to look dignified. Given that he was a kiwi bird with twigs in his feathers, the effect was more "confused hedge" than "noble hobbit."\n\n"Fun fact," Kaia said. "The hobbit holes come in different scales. The bigger ones were used when they filmed scenes meant to make the actors look small, and the smaller ones were used to make Gandalf look big."\n\n"Movie magic," Biscuit nodded wisely. "Just like how I look enormous and impressive to all the worms I meet. It's all about perspective."\n\n"You ARE enormous compared to worms."\n\n"Thank you, Kaia. That's the nicest thing you've ever said to me."\n\nThey walked around the whole set, crossing the little bridge, passing the Mill, and eventually ending up at the Green Dragon Inn, where Kaia got a ginger beer and Biscuit got a saucer of water (he tried to order "a pint of your finest worm juice" but that wasn't on the menu).\n\nAfter Hobbiton, they drove to Hamilton, the Waikato's biggest city and the fourth-largest city in New Zealand. It sits right on the banks of the Waikato River, which — fun fact — is the longest river in New Zealand, stretching 425 kilometres from Lake Taupō all the way to the sea.\n\n"That's a LOT of river," Biscuit said.\n\n"Yep. And Hamilton has the Hamilton Gardens, which are amazing — they've got gardens from all around the world. Italian Renaissance gardens, Japanese gardens, Chinese Scholar gardens, Indian gardens..."\n\n"Any gardens specifically dedicated to growing snacks?"\n\n"There's a kitchen garden."\n\n"CLOSE ENOUGH."\n\nThey also passed through Cambridge, a pretty town nearby that's known for its horse breeding and tree-lined streets. It has a very English feel to it — all tidy and posh.\n\n"This town has more horses than people," Kaia said.\n\n"Now you know how I feel being the only talking kiwi," Biscuit sighed.\n\nBut the highlight of the Waikato — the thing that made Kaia's jaw drop further than it had ever dropped before — was the Waitomo Caves.\n\nWaitomo is a system of limestone caves that have been forming for millions of years. Water has slowly carved out enormous underground chambers and tunnels, creating a hidden world beneath the farmland above. But the REALLY magical part? Glowworms.\n\nKaia and Biscuit boarded a small boat that drifted into the darkness of the cave. At first, everything was pitch black. Biscuit gripped Kaia's sleeve with his tiny foot.\n\n"I can't see anything," he whispered. "What if there are underground monsters? What if there are cave trolls? What if there are —"\n\n"Look up," Kaia whispered.\n\nBiscuit looked up. And went completely silent.\n\nThe ceiling of the cave was covered — absolutely COVERED — in thousands upon thousands of tiny blue-green lights. Glowworms. They hung from the cave roof like living stars, their bioluminescent glow turning the dark cave into an underground galaxy. The lights reflected off the still water beneath the boat, making it look like they were floating through space.\n\n"Oh," Biscuit breathed. "Oh, WOW."\n\nFor a full minute, neither of them said a word. They just drifted through the glowing wonderland, mouths open, hearts full.\n\nThen Biscuit whispered, "Kaia. I think this is the most beautiful thing I have ever seen. And I once saw a worm that was shaped like the letter B, which I took as a personal sign from the universe."\n\nKaia snorted with laughter, which echoed through the cave. "The glowworms are actually the larvae of a type of fungus gnat," she whispered. "They glow to attract insects. The light is produced by a chemical reaction in their bodies."\n\n"Don't ruin this with SCIENCE," Biscuit hissed. "They're MAGIC. They're STARS. Let me have this."\n\nAfter the cave tour, they emerged blinking into the daylight. Biscuit was so moved by the experience that he waddled in a dazed circle for three minutes.\n\n"Right," Kaia said, consulting her map. "Waikato: done! We saw Hobbiton, the longest river in NZ, Hamilton city, and the glowworms of Waitomo. I think we crushed it."\n\n"We forgot the most important thing," Biscuit said.\n\n"What?"\n\n"Cows. We didn't PET any cows."\n\n"Biscuit, a cow would step on you. You're the size of a football."\n\n"I would befriend the cow first. I'm very charming."\n\n"You told a seagull it had 'menacing eyes' yesterday."\n\n"That was a COMPLIMENT in seagull culture!" Biscuit paused. "Probably. Anyway — where to next?"\n\nKaia grinned. "Bay of Plenty. Te Moana-a-Toi. There's a place called Rotorua there that apparently smells like rotten eggs."\n\nBiscuit perked up. "Rotten eggs? Why?"\n\n"Geothermal activity. Boiling mud pools, geysers, hot springs — the whole ground is basically cooking."\n\n"A town that smells like farts? Kaia, this trip just keeps getting better. ONWARD!"\n\nAnd so they left the rolling green hills and underground galaxies of the Waikato behind and headed east, towards the bubbling, steaming, slightly stinky wonders of the Bay of Plenty.`,
