    story: `The Bay of Plenty — Te Moana-a-Toi — was named by Captain Cook, who sailed past in 1769 and noticed the local Māori communities were thriving with plentiful food and resources. So he basically said, "Wow, there's heaps of stuff here," and called it the Bay of Plenty. Original? Not really. Accurate? Absolutely.\n\n"I already love it," Biscuit declared. "Plenty of WHAT, though? Snacks? Please say snacks."\n\n"Well, kiwifruit, for one," Kaia said. "The Bay of Plenty grows about 80 percent of New Zealand's kiwifruit. There are kiwifruit orchards everywhere."\n\nBiscuit stopped walking. "Kiwi. Fruit."\n\n"Yes...?"\n\n"A fruit. Named after MY species. A fruit that looks like a small, brown, fuzzy version of ME." Biscuit's eye twitched. "I find this deeply offensive, Kaia. It would be like if someone named a lumpy brown potato after YOU."\n\n"I think you're overthinking this."\n\n"I am EXACTLY the right amount of thinking this." But Biscuit grudgingly admitted that kiwifruit were delicious after Kaia peeled one and gave him a slice. He ate it while muttering "identity theft" under his breath.\n\nTheir first stop was Tauranga, the Bay of Plenty's largest city, and its famous beach suburb Mount Maunganui — known to locals simply as "The Mount." Mount Maunganui is a 232-metre volcanic cone at the end of a sandy peninsula, with a gorgeous beach wrapping around it. It's one of the most popular beach spots in all of New Zealand.\n\n"Now THAT is a beach," Kaia said, gazing at the long stretch of golden sand and turquoise water. Surfers dotted the waves, and the air smelled like salt and sunscreen.\n\n"I want to surf," Biscuit announced.\n\nKaia looked at him. Really looked at him. He was a kiwi bird. He was round. He had no arms. His legs were the thickness of pencils.\n\n"You want to SURF?"\n\n"How hard can it be? You just stand on a board. I stand on things all the time. I'm standing RIGHT NOW."\n\nAgainst her better judgement, Kaia rented the smallest surfboard she could find (still about four times the size of Biscuit) and carried it to the water's edge. She placed Biscuit on it in the shallows.\n\n"I am a NATURAL," Biscuit crowed, balancing on the board in ankle-deep water. "I was born for this. I am the kiwi bird Kelly Slater. I am —"\n\nA wave approximately fifteen centimetres high rolled in and knocked him clean off the board. He tumbled through the foam like a tennis ball in a washing machine and washed up on the sand looking like a soggy brown pom-pom.\n\n"THE OCEAN IS TRYING TO KILL ME," he spluttered.\n\n"That wave was smaller than my hand."\n\n"It was a ROGUE WAVE. A TSUNAMI. I barely survived." He shook himself, spraying water everywhere, and somehow his feathers puffed up so much he looked like a brown dandelion. "I am never surfing again. Surfing is cancelled."\n\nAfter the Great Surfing Disaster of Mount Maunganui, they headed inland to Rotorua — and boy, did they smell it before they saw it.\n\n"What," Biscuit said slowly, "is that SMELL?"\n\n"Hydrogen sulphide gas," Kaia said, trying not to laugh. "Rotorua sits on a massive geothermal area. There's volcanic activity underground, which means boiling mud pools, geysers, hot springs, and yes — a smell like rotten eggs everywhere."\n\n"It smells like a thousand eggs died and nobody cleaned it up!"\n\n"You get used to it."\n\n"I will NEVER get used to it. My nostrils are burning. Do kiwis even HAVE nostrils? MINE ARE BURNING REGARDLESS."\n\nDespite the smell (which honestly, you really DO get used to after about ten minutes), Rotorua was absolutely amazing. The geothermal area called Te Puia was like visiting another planet. Boiling mud pools went BLORP BLORP BLORP, sending up splashes of thick grey mud. Steam hissed from cracks in the ground. The earth itself was stained orange, yellow, and white from mineral deposits.\n\nAnd then there was the Pōhutu Geyser — the largest active geyser in the Southern Hemisphere. Kaia and Biscuit watched as pressure built up underground, and then WHOOOOSH — a massive column of boiling water blasted up to 30 metres into the air, roaring like a dragon.\n\nBiscuit screamed and hid behind Kaia's leg. "THE GROUND IS EXPLODING!"\n\n"It's a geyser! It does this regularly! It's perfectly safe from here!"\n\n"NOTHING ABOUT EXPLODING GROUND IS SAFE, KAIA!"\n\nRotorua is also famous for its Māori cultural experiences. The area has a long, rich Māori history, and many local iwi share their culture with visitors through traditional performances, hāngī feasts (where food is cooked in an underground pit using hot stones — basically the Earth itself is the oven), and guided tours of sacred sites.\n\n"The hāngī food is incredible," Kaia said, eating tender chicken and vegetables that had been steamed underground. "The earth cooked this!"\n\n"The LAVA cooked this," Biscuit corrected, nibbling on a kumara. "We are eating lava food. We are basically dragons." He paused. "Very small, flightless dragons."\n\nThey also visited Whakatāne, a smaller town further east along the Bay of Plenty coast. Whakatāne is one of the sunniest places in New Zealand and has a strong Māori history — the town's name comes from a famous story about a waka (canoe) arrival.\n\n"From here you can see Whakaari, or White Island," Kaia said, pointing out to sea at the distant volcanic island that was gently steaming on the horizon. "It's New Zealand's most active volcano."\n\n"I can SEE it STEAMING," Biscuit said. "From HERE. That is an ACTIVELY ANGRY mountain in the OCEAN. This country is WILD."\n\n"That's what makes it exciting!"\n\n"You and I have VERY different definitions of exciting. My definition involves biscuits. Your definition involves potential volcanic doom."\n\nAs the sun set over the Bay of Plenty, turning everything golden, Kaia and Biscuit sat on the beach at Mount Maunganui. Kaia's hair was salty, Biscuit's feathers were still slightly damp from his surfing incident, and they were both tired and happy.\n\n"Bay of Plenty fun fact," Kaia said. "The name Te Moana-a-Toi refers to the sea of Toi, a famous Māori ancestor. And the whole region really does feel plentiful — sunshine, beaches, fruit, geothermal wonders..."\n\n"And rotten egg smell. Very plentiful rotten egg smell."\n\n"That too." Kaia looked at her map. "Next up: Gisborne. Tairāwhiti. It's the easternmost city in the world — the first place on Earth to see the sunrise each day."\n\nBiscuit perked up. "The FIRST? Before EVERYONE ELSE?"\n\n"Yep. The very first rays of sun each new day hit Gisborne before anywhere else on the planet."\n\n"That's incredibly cool. Does this mean I have to wake up early?"\n\n"If you want to see it, yes."\n\n"Hmm. How early?"\n\n"Before dawn."\n\nBiscuit looked pained. "I'll... consider it. Now let's go. My feathers are finally dry and I'd like to keep them that way."\n\nAnd so they packed up and headed east, towards the sunrise capital of the world.`,
