    story: `Kaia's alarm went off at 5:14 AM. She was not happy about it. But she was even less happy about the sound Biscuit made when she tried to wake him up — a noise somewhere between a deflating balloon and an angry cat.\n\n"WHAT TIME IS IT?" Biscuit squawked from inside the blanket cocoon he had built on the motel pillow.\n\n"Early. Come on. We're watching the sunrise."\n\n"The sun rises every day, Kaia. It's not going anywhere. It'll rise again tomorrow. We could sleep in and catch the next one."\n\n"Not from Gisborne we can't. We're only here today. And this is the first place in the WORLD to see the sunrise. Tairāwhiti literally means 'the coast upon which the sun shines across the water.' Come ON."\n\nBiscuit grumbled, groaned, and complained the entire way to the lookout at Kaiti Hill, which overlooks Gisborne city and the Pacific Ocean. He complained about the cold. He complained about the dark. He complained about a rock that looked at him funny. But then the sky started to change.\n\nFirst, a thin line of deep orange appeared on the horizon. Then pink. Then gold. The clouds caught fire with colour, and the ocean turned from black to deep blue to shimmering silver. And then, right there, before anyone else on the entire planet Earth, the sun peeked over the edge of the Pacific Ocean and sent its first rays streaming across the water and onto the coast of Gisborne.\n\nKaia held her breath. It was spectacular.\n\nBiscuit sniffed. "I'm not crying," he said, though his eyes were definitely wet. "It's the wind. There's wind in my eyes."\n\n"It's completely still this morning."\n\n"EMOTIONAL wind. It's a type of wind you wouldn't understand."\n\nGisborne is a small, sunny city on the east coast of the North Island. It's the most easterly city in the world, which means every single day, the people of Gisborne see the sun before anyone else. On New Year's Eve, thousands of people come here to be the first to celebrate the new year.\n\n"Imagine being the first person on Earth to have breakfast," Biscuit mused. "Every single day. That's power, Kaia. That's REAL power."\n\nAfter the sunrise, they explored the city. Gisborne has a strong connection to early New Zealand history — it was here, at Kaiti Beach, that Captain James Cook first set foot in New Zealand in October 1769. A statue and monuments mark the spot where his ship, the Endeavour, landed.\n\n"He sailed all the way from England," Kaia said, reading a plaque. "Can you imagine being on a wooden ship for MONTHS crossing the ocean, and then seeing this coast appear on the horizon?"\n\n"I can barely imagine being on a boat for five minutes without being sick," Biscuit said. "So no. But it does sound impressive."\n\nThe encounter between Cook's crew and the local Māori iwi, Te Aitanga-a-Māhaki and Rongowhakaata, didn't go well at first — there were misunderstandings and conflict. Cook actually named the river here "Poverty Bay" because he couldn't get the supplies he wanted, which the locals find a bit rude (understandably). The region prefers its Māori name, Tairāwhiti.\n\n"Imagine someone coming to YOUR house, not getting free snacks, and then naming your house 'No Snacks Bay,'" Biscuit said, outraged on behalf of everyone.\n\n"That's actually a pretty good analogy."\n\n"I have my moments."\n\nGisborne and the Tairāwhiti region have incredibly deep Māori cultural roots. The area is one of the heartlands of Māori language and tradition, with beautiful carved meeting houses (wharenui), and many people here speak te reo Māori as part of everyday life.\n\nThey visited a stunning meeting house where the carved figures on the walls depicted ancestors and legends. The carvings were intricate and powerful — each swirl and line told a story.\n\n"These carvings are hundreds of years of history and knowledge preserved in wood," Kaia said quietly, tracing the patterns with her eyes.\n\n"They're like books made of trees," Biscuit said. And for once, he wasn't being sarcastic. He genuinely looked impressed.\n\nThe Gisborne region is also famous for its wine and citrus orchards. The long sunny days and fertile soil make it perfect for growing grapes, and the Chardonnay from here is some of the best in the country.\n\n"No wine for me, obviously," said Kaia. "But I did read that Gisborne is sometimes called the Chardonnay Capital of New Zealand."\n\n"Capital of a drink I can't have. Brilliant. Do they have a Worm Capital? I'd like to visit the Worm Capital."\n\n"I don't think that exists."\n\n"Then what is even the POINT of geography?"\n\nThey walked along the long stretch of beach, watching surfers catch waves. Gisborne has excellent surfing beaches, and the laid-back vibe of the whole town made Kaia feel like time moved a little slower here — in a good way.\n\nAt a local café, Kaia tried a Lemon & Paeroa (L&P), which is a classic Kiwi soft drink. "Fun fact: L&P is made in Paeroa, which is actually in the Waikato, but it's popular everywhere."\n\n"This is very bubbly," Biscuit said after dunking his beak in Kaia's glass. Then he burped — a tiny, squeaky, bird-sized burp that was possibly the most ridiculous sound Kaia had ever heard.\n\nShe laughed so hard that L&P came out of her nose.\n\n"THAT," said Biscuit triumphantly, "is the funniest thing that has happened on this entire trip."\n\n"It HURTS," Kaia wheezed, but she was still laughing.\n\nAs they prepared to leave Gisborne, Kaia took one last look at the coast where the sun had risen that morning. There was something special about being in the place where each new day begins. It felt like anything was possible.\n\n"Fun fact for the road," she said. "On January 1st, 2000 — the new millennium — Gisborne was the first city in the world to see the sunrise of the year 2000. People came from everywhere to celebrate here."\n\n"The first sunrise of a thousand years," Biscuit said. "That's actually pretty epic. Even by my extremely high standards of epicness."\n\n"Next stop: Hawke's Bay. Te Matau-a-Māui. Apparently there's a whole city built in Art Deco style, and the biggest gannet colony on the mainland."\n\n"Gannets?" Biscuit's feathers ruffled. "Those are big birds, right? With the stabby beaks?"\n\n"They're seabirds, yes."\n\n"Great. More birds that can fly. Making me look bad." He sighed dramatically. "Let's go. I'll face these show-off gannets with dignity."\n\nHe then tripped over his own foot getting into the car.\n\n"THAT WAS DIGNIFIED," he shouted. "THAT WAS A DIGNIFIED TRIP."`,
