    story: `Hawke's Bay — Te Matau-a-Māui, which means "the fish hook of Māui" — is one of those places that makes you feel like you've accidentally stepped into a different time period. Specifically, the 1930s.\n\n"Why does this town look like an old-timey movie?" Biscuit asked as they walked down the main street of Napier, the region's most famous city.\n\nAnd he had a point. Napier is unlike any other city in New Zealand. Almost every building in the town centre is built in Art Deco style — think geometric shapes, zigzag patterns, pastel colours, and fancy decorative details. It looks like the set of a film about glamorous 1930s detectives.\n\n"In 1931, Napier was hit by a massive earthquake," Kaia explained. "A 7.8 magnitude quake that destroyed most of the city. It was one of the worst natural disasters in New Zealand's history."\n\n"That's awful," Biscuit said, his usual sarcasm nowhere to be found.\n\n"It was. But the city rebuilt incredibly quickly — and because it was the 1930s, they rebuilt everything in the Art Deco style that was popular at the time. So now Napier has one of the best collections of Art Deco architecture in the WORLD. People come from everywhere to see it."\n\nBiscuit looked up at the buildings with new appreciation. The clean lines, the symmetrical patterns, the sunrise motifs above the doorways — every building told the story of a city that picked itself up and rebuilt itself into something beautiful.\n\n"That's actually really inspiring," Biscuit said. "Imagine losing everything and then going, 'Right. Let's rebuild, but let's make it FANCY.' What legends."\n\nNapier even hosts an annual Art Deco Festival where people dress up in 1930s clothing — think flapper dresses, top hats, old-fashioned cars driving through the streets, and jazz music playing on every corner.\n\n"I would look EXCELLENT in a tiny top hat," Biscuit said. "Someone should make one. Kiwi-bird-sized. Just for me."\n\n"I'm not making you a top hat."\n\n"You lack vision, Kaia."\n\nNext door to Napier is the city of Hastings, which is the other major centre in Hawke's Bay. Together, Napier and Hastings are sometimes called "The Twin Cities." Hastings is surrounded by orchards and vineyards, because Hawke's Bay has some of the best grape-growing conditions in New Zealand.\n\n"Hawke's Bay is one of the most important wine regions in the country," Kaia read. "The warm, dry climate is perfect for growing grapes, and the wine from here is exported all over the world."\n\n"I cannot drink wine," Biscuit reminded her. "I am a bird."\n\n"I know. I can't either. I'm eleven."\n\n"So this information is useless to both of us. And yet here we are, learning it. Education is wild."\n\nBut the thing Biscuit had been both dreading and anticipating was the gannet colony at Cape Kidnappers. Cape Kidnappers is a dramatic rocky headland that juts out into the sea at the southern end of Hawke's Bay, and it's home to the largest mainland gannet colony in the world — about 20,000 birds.\n\n"Twenty. Thousand. Birds." Biscuit repeated slowly. "Birds that can FLY. Birds with WINGS that WORK. While I — I have these." He flapped his tiny, useless wing stubs. They moved about one centimetre.\n\n"Kiwi birds are special in other ways," Kaia said kindly.\n\n"NAME ONE."\n\n"You have the best sense of smell of any bird. Your nostrils are at the tip of your beak, which is unique. You can sniff out food underground."\n\n"Oh." Biscuit paused. "That IS pretty cool. I'm basically a truffle pig. But cuter."\n\nThey took a tractor-pulled trailer along the beach to reach the colony, and when they arrived, it was CHAOTIC. Thousands of gannets packed together on the cliff, honking, squawking, and crash-landing everywhere. Gannets are large white seabirds with yellowish heads and black-tipped wings, and they catch fish by dive-bombing into the ocean from great heights at speeds up to 145 kilometres per hour.\n\n"They dive at 145 KPH?!" Biscuit yelped as he watched a gannet plummet into the sea like a feathered missile. "That's faster than a car! That's faster than— LOOK OUT, ANOTHER ONE!"\n\nGannets were crash-landing all around them with all the grace of thrown cricket balls. They'd come in too fast, overshoot their nest, bump into their partner, get squawked at, look confused, and try again.\n\n"They're so CLUMSY," Biscuit giggled. "And I thought I was bad at landing. These guys are professionals and they STILL wipe out!"\n\n"They're better at the ocean diving part."\n\n"Sure, but the LANDING! Look at that one — it just ploughed straight into that other one! And now they're arguing about it! This is the best show I've ever seen!"\n\nFor an hour, Biscuit sat mesmerised by the gannet colony's soap opera of crash-landings, turf wars, and extremely loud neighbourly disputes. He provided running commentary like a tiny sports announcer.\n\n"And coming in on the LEFT we have a large male gannet — he's approaching the cliff — he's coming in hot — WAY too hot — he's not going to make it — AND HE'S TAKEN OUT THREE OTHERS! UNBELIEVABLE! THE CROWD GOES WILD!"\n\n"There is no crowd. It's just us."\n\n"I am a crowd of ONE, Kaia, and I am WILDLY entertained."\n\nThe Māori name for Hawke's Bay, Te Matau-a-Māui, comes from the legend that the entire bay is shaped like the fish hook that the great ancestor Māui used to fish up the North Island from the ocean. According to the story, the North Island is Te Ika-a-Māui — the fish of Māui — and the bay is where his hook caught.\n\n"So the whole North Island is a giant fish?" Biscuit said. "And we're walking around ON the fish?"\n\n"According to the legend, yes."\n\n"That is significantly more terrifying than the volcanoes."\n\nBefore leaving, they stopped at a fruit stall and Kaia loaded up on Hawke's Bay stonefruit — peaches, nectarines, and plums that tasted like sunshine.\n\n"These peaches are unreal," Kaia said, juice running down her chin.\n\nBiscuit had found a worm in one of the orchard fields and was equally delighted. "Hawke's Bay worm. Vintage. Fruity undertones. Excellent mouthfeel."\n\n"Please stop describing worms like a food critic."\n\n"I am a CONNOISSEUR, Kaia."\n\nAs they left Hawke's Bay, Kaia looked back at Napier's Art Deco skyline one last time. A city destroyed by earthquake and rebuilt into something extraordinary. It was a good reminder that tough times don't last, but tough people — and tough towns — do.\n\n"Next stop: Taranaki," she told Biscuit. "There's a volcano there that looks exactly like Mount Fuji in Japan."\n\n"ANOTHER volcano?! This country is just VOLCANOES!"\n\n"Technically this one is dormant."\n\n"They're ALL dormant until they're NOT, Kaia! That's how dormant WORKS!"\n\nBut despite his protests, Biscuit was already waddling towards the car. Because deep down (very deep down, underneath all the sarcasm and snack obsession), Biscuit loved this adventure just as much as Kaia did.\n\nHe just wasn't going to ADMIT it.`,
