    story: `You could see it from ages away. A perfect, cone-shaped mountain rising from flat green farmland, its peak dusted with snow, looking like it had been drawn by someone who was asked to draw the world's most perfect mountain.\n\n"It looks like a painting," Kaia breathed.\n\n"It looks like a VOLCANO," Biscuit corrected, eyeing Mt Taranaki with deep suspicion. "Because it IS a volcano. A 2,518-metre tall volcano sitting right there, being all picturesque and menacing."\n\nMt Taranaki (also called Mt Egmont, though most people use the Māori name) is the absolute icon of the Taranaki region. It's so symmetrical and perfectly shaped that it was used as a stand-in for Mt Fuji in the Tom Cruise movie The Last Samurai.\n\n"Our mountain is a movie star," Kaia said.\n\n"Our mountain is a TICKING TIME BOMB with good cheekbones," Biscuit muttered.\n\nThe Taranaki region sits on the west coast of the North Island, and its main city is New Plymouth — a creative, vibrant coastal city that punches well above its weight for things to do.\n\nTheir first stop was the Len Lye Centre, an art museum in New Plymouth that is one of the coolest buildings Kaia had ever seen. The outside is covered in shimmering, reflective stainless steel that mirrors the sky and changes with the light. It's dedicated to Len Lye, a New Zealand artist who was a pioneer of kinetic (moving) art and experimental filmmaking.\n\n"The BUILDING is art," Kaia said, staring at the way the steel panels caught the sunlight.\n\n"The building looks like a giant piece of tin foil that someone folded really artistically," Biscuit said. "I mean that as a compliment. I think."\n\nInside, the kinetic sculptures were mesmerising — huge steel sculptures that moved, twisted, and vibrated. One enormous curved steel strip rocked back and forth, making a deep humming sound that you could feel in your chest.\n\n"It's ALIVE!" Biscuit shrieked, leaping behind Kaia's leg as a sculpture started spinning.\n\n"It's ART."\n\n"Art shouldn't MOVE, Kaia! Art should sit still on walls and be QUIET!"\n\n"That's a very narrow definition of art."\n\n"I have very narrow everything. I'm a KIWI BIRD."\n\nAfter Biscuit recovered from being startled by modern art, they walked along the New Plymouth Coastal Walkway — a 13-kilometre path that follows the coastline and is one of the best walks in New Zealand. Along the way, they crossed the Te Rewa Rewa Bridge, a stunning white bridge that frames Mt Taranaki perfectly in its curved opening. It's shaped a bit like a whale skeleton and is insanely photogenic.\n\n"Take my photo!" Biscuit demanded, posing on the bridge railing with Mt Taranaki behind him. He tried to look mysterious and brooding. He looked like a potato with eyes.\n\n"Beautiful," Kaia lied, taking the photo.\n\n"I'm going to use that as my profile picture for everything."\n\n"You don't HAVE any profiles. You're a bird."\n\n"That you KNOW of."\n\nTaranaki has a rich Māori history. According to legend, Mt Taranaki used to live in the centre of the North Island with the other mountains — Tongariro, Ruapehu, and Ngāuruhoe. But Taranaki fell in love with the beautiful Pīhanga (a smaller mountain), which made Tongariro furious because Pīhanga was HIS partner. The two mountains fought an enormous battle, and Taranaki lost. Heartbroken, Taranaki carved his way to the coast, his tears forming the Whanganui River as he went. He now stands alone on the west coast, separated from the others, sometimes hiding his face in clouds because he is still sad.\n\n"That," Biscuit said, "is the most dramatic break-up story I have ever heard. And I once saw two pigeons fight over a chip."\n\n"It's beautiful though, right? Every time Taranaki is covered in clouds, it's because he's crying over Pīhanga."\n\n"I'm not going to be able to look at clouds the same way ever again."\n\nTaranaki is also known for excellent surfing. The waves along the coast here are consistent and powerful, attracting surfers from around the country. Surf Highway 45 runs along the coast south of New Plymouth, connecting a string of famous surf breaks.\n\n"Want to try surfing again?" Kaia asked innocently.\n\nBiscuit's feathers puffed out in alarm. "We agreed to NEVER speak of the Mount Maunganui incident again."\n\n"I didn't agree to that."\n\n"I am unilaterally declaring a ban on discussing my surfing history. It is now LAW."\n\nThey watched the surfers instead, and Biscuit had to admit the waves were impressive. Long, peeling walls of water that the surfers carved across with effortless grace.\n\n"I bet I could do that if I had arms," he said wistfully.\n\n"You'd need arms AND legs AND balance AND—"\n\n"Just arms would be fine, thank you. I have PLENTY of balance." He fell off the rock he was sitting on. "WIND PUSHED ME."\n\nNew Plymouth itself was a lovely city — not too big, not too small. It had great cafés, the beautiful Pukekura Park (a stunning botanical garden with lakes, waterfalls, and bush walks right in the middle of the city), and a real sense of creativity and community.\n\n"Taranaki fun fact," Kaia said. "The Taranaki region is one of New Zealand's most important energy-producing regions. There are oil and gas fields off the coast, and the region also has one of the country's first wind farms."\n\n"So there's a volcano AND oil AND gas AND wind underneath and around this place?" Biscuit shook his head. "This region is an energy drink. It's FULL of power."\n\nAs they packed up to leave, Kaia looked back at Mt Taranaki. The late afternoon light was hitting the mountain, turning its snowy peak pink and gold. A single cloud clung to the summit like a hat.\n\n"He's thinking about Pīhanga," Biscuit said quietly.\n\nKaia smiled. "Yeah. Maybe he is."\n\n"Right!" Biscuit said, snapping out of his sentimental moment. "Where to next? Somewhere with fewer tragic mountain love stories, preferably."\n\n"Manawatū-Whanganui," Kaia said. "There's a river there that's legally a person."\n\nBiscuit stopped walking. "A river. That is legally. A PERSON."\n\n"Yep."\n\n"Does it have a driver's licence?"\n\n"That's not how it works—"\n\n"Can it VOTE?"\n\n"Biscuit—"\n\n"Does it pay TAXES?"\n\n"LET ME EXPLAIN ON THE WAY!"\n\nAnd off they went, heading inland towards one of the most unique legal arrangements in the entire world.`,
