    story: `"Okay, explain this river-person thing to me," Biscuit said as they drove into the Manawatū-Whanganui region. "Because I have SO many questions."\n\n"Right," Kaia said. "So the Whanganui River — Te Awa Tupua — is the third-longest river in New Zealand. For Māori, especially the local iwi, the river is an ancestor. They have a saying: 'Ko au te awa, ko te awa ko au' — I am the river, and the river is me."\n\n"That's actually beautiful," Biscuit said.\n\n"In 2017, the New Zealand government passed a law giving the Whanganui River the same legal rights as a person. It was the first river in the world to be given this status. The idea is that the river itself can be represented in court, have its interests protected, and be treated as a living entity — which is how Māori have always seen it."\n\nBiscuit was quiet for a moment. Then: "So if someone pollutes the river, it's like... assaulting a person?"\n\n"Basically, yes. Two guardians were appointed — one from the local iwi and one from the government — to speak on behalf of the river."\n\n"The river has LAWYERS." Biscuit shook his head in amazement. "This is the best country on Earth. Can I become a legal person too? I'd like rights. And a pension."\n\n"You're a bird."\n\n"The river is WATER, Kaia. If water can be a person, a bird can be a person. I rest my case."\n\nThey visited the Whanganui River itself, and it was magnificent. It winds 290 kilometres through deep, bush-covered gorges, past ancient Māori settlements, and through some of the most remote and beautiful scenery in the North Island. You can canoe down it for days, camping along the banks.\n\n"People do multi-day canoe trips down the Whanganui," Kaia said. "It's one of New Zealand's Great Walks — except you do it by water. It's called the Whanganui Journey."\n\n"A Great Walk that isn't actually a walk? I'm confused. But also delighted, because walking is my least favourite activity. After swimming. And climbing. And basically all physical activity."\n\nThe city of Whanganui itself is a charming, artsy place sitting at the mouth of the river. It has beautiful old buildings, quirky galleries, and a real sense of history. The riverbank is lined with old steamboat wharves from the days when paddle steamers used to carry tourists up the river.\n\n"This place feels like stepping back in time," Kaia said. "In a good way."\n\n"Everything feels like stepping back in time when you're a species that's been around for millions of years," Biscuit said smugly. "Kiwi birds have been in New Zealand since before humans existed. We are ANCIENT."\n\n"And yet you can't figure out how to open a zip-lock bag."\n\n"That's a DESIGN FLAW. In the bag. Not in me."\n\nFrom Whanganui, they headed to Palmerston North — or "Palmy" as everyone calls it. Palmerston North is the main city of the Manawatū area and is home to Massey University, one of New Zealand's biggest universities.\n\n"Massey is famous for its veterinary and agricultural science programmes," Kaia read. "So if you ever need a vet, Biscuit, this is the place."\n\n"I do NOT need a vet. I am in PEAK physical condition." He paused. "My left leg does click sometimes when it's cold. And I get a bit wheezy after running. And one of my feathers is growing in sideways. But OTHER than that — peak condition."\n\nPalmerston North sits in the Manawatū plains, a flat, fertile area that's important for farming. The city's main square, The Square, is a large green park in the centre of town that's been the heart of Palmy for over a century.\n\n"Palmy fun fact," Kaia said. "This city is sometimes called the most windy city in New Zealand, competing with Wellington for the title."\n\n"I can FEEL that," Biscuit said, leaning at a 45-degree angle into the wind. His feathers were all blowing in one direction, making him look like a very startled feather duster. "I weigh almost nothing, Kaia. I could literally blow away. If I disappear, tell my story. Tell them I was brave. Tell them I was handsome."\n\n"I'll tell them you were dramatic."\n\n"SAME THING."\n\nThe Manawatū-Whanganui region is huge — it also extends up to include part of the Tongariro area, home to Tongariro National Park. This is New Zealand's oldest national park and a UNESCO World Heritage site. It contains three active volcanoes: Tongariro, Ngāuruhoe, and Ruapehu.\n\n"Mount Ngāuruhoe was used as Mount Doom in the Lord of the Rings films," Kaia said.\n\n"MOUNT DOOM?!" Biscuit's eyes went wide. "We're near MOUNT DOOM?!"\n\n"It's just a mountain. A very cool, volcanic mountain."\n\n"One does not simply WALK near Mount Doom, Kaia! That's literally the whole point of the movies!"\n\nThe Tongariro Alpine Crossing, a one-day hike across the volcanic landscape, is considered one of the best day walks in the world. You walk past emerald-coloured crater lakes, steaming vents, and alien-looking landscapes that genuinely look like they belong on another planet. Or, you know, in Mordor.\n\n"The lakes are that colour because of minerals from the volcanic activity," Kaia explained, showing Biscuit a photo. The Emerald Lakes were an impossibly vivid green-blue, sitting in dark volcanic craters like jewels.\n\n"That cannot be real," Biscuit said. "Someone has edited that photo. No water is that colour."\n\n"It's real. It's the minerals — sulphur and iron and other chemicals from the volcanoes."\n\n"So you're telling me there are bright green lakes sitting on top of active volcanoes in the middle of a national park that was used to film the lair of an evil dark lord?" Biscuit blinked. "New Zealand is the WILDEST country."\n\nAs they prepared to leave the Manawatū-Whanganui region, Kaia looked at her map. They were heading south to Wellington — the capital city of New Zealand.\n\n"Wellington!" she announced. "Te Whanganui-a-Tara. The capital. Parliament. Te Papa. The windiest city in the world."\n\n"WINDIER than Palmy?!" Biscuit looked alarmed. "Kaia, I already nearly blew away here. In Wellington, I'll need to be ANCHORED. I'll need WEIGHTS. I'll need to be tied to something heavy."\n\n"I'll put you in my backpack."\n\n"Is your backpack windproof?"\n\n"It'll have to be."\n\n"This does not inspire confidence." But Biscuit waddled to the car with determination. "Fine. Let's go meet the capital. If I blow away, I expect a statue in my honour. A big one. In a flattering pose."\n\nAnd so they drove south, towards the wild, windy, wonderful city at the bottom of the North Island.`,
