    story: `They felt Wellington before they saw it. The wind hit the car like an invisible wall as they came over the Remutaka Range, and Biscuit — who had been napping on the dashboard — was jolted awake.\n\n"WHAT WAS THAT?" he squawked.\n\n"Wind," Kaia said, gripping the steering wheel. (Obviously Kaia wasn't actually driving — she was eleven. Her Aunty Mere was driving. But Aunty Mere is very quiet and doesn't add much to the story, so let's focus on Kaia and Biscuit.)\n\n"That's not WIND. That's an ATTACK. The AIR is attacking us!"\n\nWellington — Te Whanganui-a-Tara — is famous for many things, but its wind might be the most notorious. Sitting at the bottom of the North Island, squeezed between hills on a harbour that funnels wind like a giant blowdryer, Wellington is often called the windiest city in the world.\n\n"Wellingtonians are a tough breed," Kaia said as they walked along the waterfront, both of them leaning forward at an angle. "You have to be, to live here. People have been known to hold onto lamp posts."\n\n"I am going to hold onto YOUR lamp post," Biscuit said, gripping Kaia's jacket with his tiny feet. "I mean your ARM. You are my lamp post now."\n\nDespite the wind (or maybe because of it), Wellington is one of the coolest cities in New Zealand. It's compact, hilly, creative, and FULL of personality. It's also the capital of the country, which means this is where the government lives.\n\nThey headed straight for Parliament, where the most recognisable building is the Beehive. Designed in the 1960s, it genuinely looks like a beehive — a round, layered building that houses the executive wing of New Zealand's government.\n\n"That's where the Prime Minister works?" Biscuit asked, staring up at it.\n\n"Yep. And Members of Parliament. The whole government."\n\n"It looks like a cake. A political cake. A cake full of DECISIONS." He cocked his head. "Do they have snacks in there? Politicians must eat."\n\n"I think they have a cafeteria."\n\n"So my taxes are paying for their snacks. If I paid taxes. Which I don't. Because I'm a bird. But HYPOTHETICALLY."\n\nNext up was Te Papa Tongarewa — the Museum of New Zealand. Te Papa (which means "Our Place") is one of the best museums in the world, and it's completely FREE to visit. It sits right on the Wellington waterfront, a massive, modern building packed with exhibits about New Zealand's history, culture, and natural environment.\n\n"This place is AMAZING," Kaia said, wandering through exhibit after exhibit. There were interactive earthquake simulators (Biscuit refused to go on this — "I have had ENOUGH natural disasters, thank you"), a colossal squid specimen (one of the biggest ever found), Māori taonga (treasures), and exhibits about New Zealand's unique wildlife.\n\n"Look!" Kaia pointed at a display about kiwi birds. "That's your species!"\n\nBiscuit examined the exhibit critically. "They haven't captured my good side. Also, that model's beak is all wrong. My beak is much more distinguished." He posed next to the display. "See? Much better."\n\n"You look exactly the same."\n\n"You need glasses."\n\nWellington is also the heart of New Zealand's film industry. This is where Peter Jackson's film studios are based — Wētā Workshop created the special effects for The Lord of the Rings, The Hobbit, Avatar, and tonnes of other massive movies. Wellington is sometimes called "Wellywood."\n\n"We're in the city that made Middle-earth come to life," Kaia said reverently as they visited the Weta Workshop visitor experience, where they could see actual props, costumes, and creatures from the films.\n\n"Is that a CAVE TROLL?" Biscuit whispered, staring at an enormous sculpture.\n\n"A model of one, yes."\n\n"It's looking at me. I don't like it. Make it stop looking at me."\n\n"It's a statue. It CAN'T look at you."\n\n"Its EYES are following me, Kaia!" Biscuit hid behind her leg for the fifteenth time that day.\n\nThey rode the Wellington Cable Car — a cute red funicular railway that climbs from the city centre up to the Botanic Garden at the top of the hill. The view from the top was stunning — the whole city and harbour spread out below, with hills wrapped around the water like a green amphitheatre.\n\n"Fun fact," Kaia said. "Wellington became the capital of New Zealand in 1865 because it's in the middle of the country — between the North and South Islands. Auckland was the capital before that, but it was too far north."\n\n"So Wellington got the job because of GEOGRAPHY? Not because of talent or personality?" Biscuit scoffed. "Typical. It's not what you know, it's where you are."\n\nThe food scene in Wellington was also incredible. The city is famous for its café culture — Wellingtonians take their coffee VERY seriously. Kaia had the best hot chocolate of her life at a tiny café on Cuba Street, which is Wellington's most famous street for quirky shops, street performers, and bohemian vibes.\n\n"Cuba Street is named after the ship Cuba, which brought settlers here in 1840," Kaia read. "Not the country."\n\n"Confusing," said Biscuit, who had found a muffin crumb on the floor and was treating it like buried treasure.\n\nAs the day wound down, they stood on the waterfront and watched the Cook Strait ferry departing for the South Island. The big Interislander ferry ploughed through the choppy harbour water, heading for Picton on the other side.\n\n"Tomorrow, that's us," Kaia said. "We're crossing the Cook Strait to the South Island. Te Waipounamu."\n\nBiscuit watched the ferry nervously. The water in the strait looked... bouncy. Very bouncy. Cook Strait is known as one of the most unpredictable stretches of water in the world — the Tasman Sea and the Pacific Ocean collide here, and it can get ROUGH.\n\n"How long is the crossing?" Biscuit asked in a small voice.\n\n"About three and a half hours."\n\n"Three and a half HOURS?! On THAT water?! Kaia, I get seasick watching bath water drain. I once threw up on a puddle."\n\n"That's not possible."\n\n"It was a very SLOSHY puddle."\n\n"You'll be fine. The ferry is huge. And apparently the trip through the Marlborough Sounds at the end is one of the most beautiful boat rides in the world."\n\nBiscuit took a deep, shaky breath. "Fine. I will face the ocean. I will conquer the strait. I will NOT throw up." He paused. "I will TRY not to throw up. No promises."\n\nKaia patted his head. "That's the spirit."\n\n"It is the OPPOSITE of spirit. It is pure terror. But I appreciate the encouragement."\n\nAnd so, as Wellington's wind whipped their faces one last time and the city lights began to twinkle against the darkening harbour, Kaia and Biscuit prepared for the next leg of their adventure — crossing the Cook Strait to the South Island, where mountains, glaciers, and entirely new wonders awaited them.`,
