    story: `The ferry crossing was every bit as dramatic as Biscuit had feared. The Cook Strait served up two-metre swells, and Biscuit spent the first hour wedged into a corner of the cabin, his eyes squeezed shut, making sounds that Kaia could only describe as "distressed squeaking."\n\n"I told you," he moaned. "The ocean is my enemy. It has been my enemy since the surfing incident. We are in a FEUD."\n\nBut then the ferry entered the Marlborough Sounds — a network of sunken river valleys filled with sea water — and everything changed. The water calmed to a mirror-like stillness. Green, bush-covered hills rose on either side. It was so peaceful and beautiful that even Biscuit unclenched.\n\n"Oh," he said. "Oh, this is actually lovely."\n\n"Told you."\n\n"Don't ruin this with 'told you.' Let me have my moment of peace."\n\nThey docked in Picton (which they'd explore properly later, in the Marlborough chapter) and headed northwest to the Tasman region — Te Tai-o-Aorere.\n\nThe Tasman region is named after Abel Tasman, the Dutch explorer who was the first European to sight New Zealand in 1642. He didn't have the best visit — there was a skirmish with local Māori in Golden Bay and he left without ever setting foot on shore. But his name stuck to half the things in the area.\n\n"Imagine being famous for a place you never actually VISITED properly," Biscuit said. "That's like me being the spokesperson for flying. I can't fly. But sure, name stuff after me."\n\nThe jewel of the Tasman region is Abel Tasman National Park — New Zealand's smallest national park by area, but possibly its most beautiful. It's a coastal paradise of golden sand beaches, turquoise water, lush native bush, and sculptured granite rocks. The Abel Tasman Coast Track is one of New Zealand's Great Walks, a three-to-five day hike along the coast that connects one stunning beach to the next.\n\n"Those beaches are GOLD," Kaia gasped when they arrived. And she wasn't exaggerating — the sand in Abel Tasman really does glow golden, coloured by minerals in the granite rocks. Combined with the crystal-clear turquoise water, it looked more like a tropical island than New Zealand.\n\n"This is ridiculous," Biscuit said, standing on the golden sand. "This looks fake. This looks like someone put a filter on reality. Is this even legal? Can a beach be this beautiful and just... exist? For free? Where anyone can see it?"\n\n"Welcome to New Zealand's best-kept secret that isn't actually a secret at all."\n\nThey decided to explore by kayak. Sea kayaking is one of the most popular ways to experience Abel Tasman — you paddle along the coastline, stopping at beaches, exploring sea caves, and sometimes spotting seals, dolphins, and penguins.\n\nKaia climbed into a kayak confidently. Biscuit was placed on the front of the kayak like a tiny, nervous figurehead.\n\n"I don't like this," he announced.\n\n"You haven't even started moving yet."\n\n"I don't like it PREEMPTIVELY."\n\nKaia began paddling, and the kayak glided out into the bay. The water was so clear she could see the sandy bottom metres below, with fish darting around and seaweed swaying gently.\n\n"Okay, this is actually— SEAL! SEAL! THERE'S A SEAL!" Biscuit screamed.\n\nA New Zealand fur seal had popped its head up right next to the kayak, its whiskered face about thirty centimetres from Biscuit. The seal looked at Biscuit. Biscuit looked at the seal. The seal looked deeply unimpressed.\n\n"G-good morning," Biscuit stammered. "Lovely day for a swim. You're very... large. And wet. Please don't eat me."\n\nThe seal blinked, snorted, and dove back under the water.\n\n"WE NEARLY DIED," Biscuit said.\n\n"It wasn't interested in you at all."\n\n"It was SIZING ME UP. I saw it in its eyes. It was thinking 'that's a kiwi-bird-sized snack right there.' I KNOW that look."\n\nThey paddled to a secluded beach called Bark Bay and pulled up on the sand for lunch. The bush came right down to the water's edge, with pōhutukawa and kanuka trees leaning over the golden sand. Native birds sang in the canopy. It was so peaceful that Kaia didn't want to leave.\n\n"The main towns in the Tasman region are Richmond and Motueka," Kaia said, eating her sandwich. "Motueka is the gateway town to Abel Tasman — it's where a lot of people start their kayak or hiking trips."\n\n"Motueka," Biscuit repeated. "Mo-tu-eka. Good name. Sounds like a sneeze. A polite sneeze."\n\n"The Tasman region also has heaps of fruit orchards — apples, hops for beer, and grapes for wine. The soil and climate here are perfect for growing."\n\n"Finally, someone growing snacks. This is my kind of region."\n\nOn the way back, their kayak entered a sea cave — a large cavern carved into the cliff by centuries of waves. Inside, the water was still and green, and the rock walls echoed every sound.\n\n"Hello!" Kaia called out.\n\n"HELLO! HELLO! Hello..." the cave echoed back.\n\n"MY NAME IS BISCUIT AND I AM VERY BRAVE!" Biscuit yelled.\n\n"VERY BRAVE... VERY BRAVE... very brave..." the cave replied.\n\n"Even the CAVE agrees," Biscuit said, puffing up proudly.\n\n"It's an echo. It would agree with anything."\n\n"I HAVE BAD BALANCE AND I'M SCARED OF SEALS!" Kaia shouted.\n\n"HEY!" Biscuit objected as the cave faithfully echoed Kaia's words. "That is SLANDER! I am suing that cave!"\n\nAs they returned their kayak and dried off, Kaia reflected on the Tasman region. Golden beaches, crystal water, native bush, seals, sea caves — it was nature at its most spectacular.\n\n"Tasman fun fact," she said. "Abel Tasman National Park has split apple rock — a huge boulder in the sea that's split perfectly in half, like someone karate-chopped it. There's a Māori legend that two gods fought over it and split it during their argument."\n\n"Gods fighting over a rock. Mountains fighting over love interests. New Zealand mythology is INTENSE." Biscuit shook the last of the sea water from his feathers. "Where next?"\n\n"Nelson. Whakatū. Just next door. It's the sunniest city in New Zealand and the geographic centre of the whole country."\n\n"The CENTRE? So it's the belly button of New Zealand?"\n\n"That's... one way to put it."\n\n"I'd like to stand on the belly button. For the photo. Let's go."\n\nAnd so they headed east, from golden beaches to sunny skies, towards the very centre of Aotearoa.`,
