    famousFor: 'Centre of NZ, sunniest city, art scene',
    story: `Nelson — Whakatū — is the kind of place that makes you want to pull up a chair, sit in the sun, and stay forever. And there is a LOT of sun. Nelson is officially the sunniest city in New Zealand, getting over 2,400 hours of sunshine per year.\n\n"I can FEEL the vitamin D entering my body," Biscuit said, sprawled on a warm rock like a tiny feathered lizard. "This is it, Kaia. We're not leaving. I'm retiring here. Build me a small house on this rock. I'll live here forever."\n\n"We have eleven more regions to visit."\n\n"Postpone them. I'm PHOTOSYNTHESISING."\n\n"Birds don't photosynthesise."\n\n"I'm PIONEERING it."\n\nNelson is one of the oldest cities in New Zealand — it was one of the first places settled by European colonists in 1841. It's small compared to Auckland or Wellington, but what it lacks in size, it makes up for in charm, creativity, and incredible natural surroundings.\n\nThe thing Nelson is most famous for (besides sunshine) is being the Centre of New Zealand. There's a marker on top of a hill called Botanical Hill, right in the middle of the city, and it claims to mark the geographic centre of the country.\n\n"We HAVE to go up there," Kaia said.\n\n"Does it involve climbing?" Biscuit asked suspiciously.\n\n"A gentle walk up a hill."\n\n"Define 'gentle.'"\n\n"About twenty minutes."\n\n"Define 'minutes' in kiwi-bird units. My legs are five centimetres long. Your twenty minutes is my forty-five minutes. MINIMUM."\n\nKaia carried him up the last stretch (in her backpack, where he sat like a king on a throne), and at the top, they found the Centre of New Zealand marker. A plaque on a post marked the spot, and the 360-degree views of Nelson, Tasman Bay, and the surrounding mountains were gorgeous.\n\n"I am standing in the EXACT CENTRE of New Zealand," Biscuit announced, hopping onto the marker. "Everything revolves around ME. I am the middle. I am the CORE. I am—"\n\n"Actually, the marker isn't perfectly accurate. It was originally a survey point used in the 1870s, and the actual geographic centre might be slightly different depending on how you calculate it. But it's close enough."\n\n"You just ruined my moment."\n\n"Facts don't care about your moments."\n\n"RUDE."\n\nDespite the technicality, the spot felt special. Standing there, you could look north towards the Tasman region they'd just visited, south towards the mountains, and feel like you were balanced right in the heart of the country.\n\nNelson is also famous for its thriving arts scene. The city is packed with galleries, studios, and workshops — painters, sculptors, potters, glass-blowers, jewellers, and all sorts of creative types have made Nelson their home, drawn by the light, the lifestyle, and the scenery.\n\n"Artists love Nelson because of the quality of the light," Kaia said. "All that sunshine creates really clear, bright conditions for painting and photography."\n\n"I should be an artist's model," Biscuit said, striking a pose. "I have excellent bone structure."\n\n"You're round."\n\n"Roundness IS a bone structure, Kaia. A very AESTHETICALLY PLEASING bone structure."\n\nThey visited a glass-blowing studio where an artist was making a beautiful vase from molten glass. The furnace roared, and the glass glowed orange-red as the artist twisted and blew it into shape.\n\n"That glass is over 1,000 degrees," Kaia whispered to Biscuit.\n\n"I am standing VERY far away," Biscuit whispered back from behind a display cabinet. "My feathers are FLAMMABLE. I am basically kindling with eyes."\n\nThe World of Wearable Art (WOW) originated in Nelson. It started in 1987 when a local artist had the idea of taking art off the wall and putting it on the human body. The WOW show has since become a massive international event (now held in Wellington), where designers create incredible, wild, gravity-defying outfits that are more sculpture than clothing.\n\n"Imagine wearing a dress made of bicycle parts," Kaia said, looking at photos of past WOW entries. "Or a suit made of recycled cans."\n\n"I once wore a leaf on my head for three days because it landed there and I didn't notice. Does that count?"\n\n"Not really."\n\n"It was very avant-garde."\n\nNelson's Saturday Market is one of the best in the country — a bustling, colourful market where locals sell fresh produce, handmade crafts, baked goods, and street food. Kaia tried a feijoa smoothie and declared it the best thing she'd tasted all trip.\n\n"Feijoa!" Biscuit said. "I was sitting on a feijoa when we first met. Remember? In your garden? Before you SCREAMED at me?"\n\n"You were a TALKING BIRD in my GARDEN. Of course I screamed."\n\n"You hurt my feelings that day, Kaia. I've never fully recovered."\n\n"You seem fine."\n\n"On the OUTSIDE. Inside, I am a broken kiwi." He ate a piece of feijoa. "Okay, I'm less broken now. This is delicious."\n\nThey also visited Tahunanui Beach — "Tahuna" to locals — a lovely, long sandy beach right on the edge of the city. It's one of those rare places where you can be in the city centre in five minutes but feel like you're on a holiday beach.\n\n"Nelson fun fact," Kaia said. "Nelson is technically a 'unitary authority,' which means it governs itself separately from the Tasman region next door, even though they're very close neighbours. Nelson is one of the smallest regions in New Zealand by area, but it has a really distinct identity."\n\n"Small but mighty," Biscuit said. "Just like me."\n\n"You're small, I'll give you that."\n\n"The MIGHTY part is implied!"\n\nAs they prepared to leave Nelson, Kaia noticed how many people were out walking, cycling, kayaking, and generally just... enjoying life. Nelson had a pace that felt different from the other cities — relaxed, creative, and sunny in every sense of the word.\n\n"I could live here," she said.\n\n"I already told you, I AM living here. I declared it on that rock. It's OFFICIAL."\n\n"You can live here after we finish the trip. Next up: Marlborough. Tauihu. Wine country, the Marlborough Sounds, and the ferry terminal at Picton."\n\n"We're going BACK to where we started on the South Island? That seems inefficient."\n\n"It's nearby! And we just drove through it to get here. Now we're properly exploring it."\n\n"Fine. But if I have to get on another boat, I want a life jacket. A tiny, kiwi-bird-sized life jacket. With my name on it."\n\n"I'll see what I can do."\n\n"In sparkly letters."\n\n"Don't push it."\n\nAnd off they went, from the sunny centre of New Zealand to the sounds and vineyards of Marlborough.`,
