    famousFor: 'Wine, Marlborough Sounds, ferry terminal',
    story: `Marlborough — Tauihu — is a region of contrasts. On one side, you have the Marlborough Sounds: a vast, intricate maze of waterways, islands, and bush-covered peninsulas that look like a giant green jigsaw puzzle dropped into the sea. On the other, you have the flat, sunny Wairau Plain, covered in row after row of grapevines as far as the eye can see.\n\n"Grapes to the left of me, ocean to the right," Biscuit sang. "Here I am, stuck in the middle with you."\n\n"Did you just quote a 1970s song?"\n\n"I am a bird of CULTURE, Kaia."\n\nThey started in Picton, the small town at the head of Queen Charlotte Sound where the Interislander and Bluebridge ferries arrive from Wellington. Picton is basically the front door of the South Island — everyone who takes the ferry lands here.\n\n"This is where we arrived!" Biscuit said. "I remember because I was busy trying not to vomit."\n\n"You did vomit."\n\n"I vomited with GRACE and DIGNITY and we agreed never to mention it again."\n\n"We did NOT agree to that."\n\nPicton is small but charming, nestled at the end of the sound with fishing boats in the harbour and green hills rising steeply on either side. It's the starting point for the Queen Charlotte Track, a 70-kilometre walking and mountain biking trail that winds through the Sounds.\n\nThe Marlborough Sounds themselves are extraordinary. Created when river valleys were flooded by rising sea levels after the last ice age, they form over 1,500 kilometres of coastline — that's more coastline than in the entire rest of the South Island combined.\n\n"Fifteen HUNDRED kilometres?" Biscuit said. "That's... a lot of edges. New Zealand really went all out on the coastline in this area."\n\n"The Sounds are home to dolphins, seals, penguins, and rare seabirds," Kaia said. "And the water is incredibly sheltered, so it's perfect for kayaking, sailing, and fishing."\n\nThey took a water taxi through Queen Charlotte Sound, and it was like gliding through a painting. The water was deep blue-green, the bush was dense and bright, and every bend revealed another hidden bay or tiny island. Occasionally, a dolphin would arc through the water nearby.\n\n"I count four dolphins," Kaia said, leaning over the edge of the boat.\n\nBiscuit was sitting firmly in the centre of the boat, as far from all edges as physically possible. "I trust your count. I will be observing the dolphins from a SAFE DISTANCE. A distance at which I cannot fall into the water. Which is where I am NOW."\n\nA dolphin leaped out of the water right next to the boat, and Biscuit screamed so loudly the water taxi driver flinched.\n\n"IT'S COMING FOR ME!"\n\n"It's PLAYING! Dolphins are FRIENDLY!"\n\n"FRIENDLY things don't JUMP at you! That's AGGRESSIVE FRIENDLINESS!"\n\nFrom Picton, they drove to Blenheim, the main town of Marlborough and the heart of New Zealand's wine country. Marlborough produces over 75 percent of all New Zealand wine, and it's especially famous for its Sauvignon Blanc — a white wine that's exported to countries all over the world.\n\n"The Wairau Valley has the perfect combination of long sunshine hours, cool nights, and free-draining soil," Kaia read from a sign at a vineyard. "This creates intense, flavourful grapes."\n\n"That is a LOT of information about grapes," Biscuit said, looking at the vineyards stretching to the horizon. "I have never seen this many grapes. This is a grape EMPIRE. A grapire."\n\n"That's not a word."\n\n"It is NOW."\n\nThe vineyards were beautiful — orderly rows of vines with bright green leaves, stretching across the flat plain with mountains in the background. Even though Kaia couldn't taste the wine, she tried some grape juice at a vineyard café and declared it incredible.\n\n"Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc is famous worldwide," Kaia said. "When people overseas think of New Zealand wine, they usually think of Marlborough."\n\n"So this region is basically New Zealand's most famous export that we're too young to drink," Biscuit said. "Cool. Very cool. I'll just sit here and eat actual grapes like a commoner."\n\nA vineyard cat appeared and sat near them. Biscuit eyed it nervously.\n\n"That cat is looking at me the way I look at worms," he said. "With HUNGER."\n\n"Vineyard cats catch mice, not kiwi birds."\n\n"Today mice. Tomorrow, birds. I know how ambition works."\n\nBlenheim itself is a pleasant, sunny town — the Marlborough region gets similar sunshine hours to Nelson, making it one of the sunniest parts of New Zealand. The town has a lovely park, some good cafés, and the Omaka Aviation Heritage Centre, which has an amazing collection of World War I aircraft.\n\n"Fun fact," Kaia said. "The Marlborough region also has a flourishing mussel and salmon farming industry in the Sounds. Green-lipped mussels from Marlborough are exported around the world."\n\n"Green-lipped mussels?" Biscuit made a face. "That sounds like something a witch would put in a potion. 'Eye of newt, green-lipped mussel, toe of frog...'"\n\n"They're actually delicious. And very nutritious."\n\n"I'll stick to worms, thank you. I know where I stand with worms."\n\nAs they drove back through the Sounds towards their next destination, Kaia thought about how Marlborough was a perfect example of New Zealand's diversity. In one region, you could go from rugged ocean coastline to peaceful sheltered waterways to sun-baked vineyard plains — all within an hour's drive.\n\n"Marlborough fun fact," she told Biscuit. "The Māori name for the top of the South Island area is Tauihu, which means 'the prow of the canoe.' It comes from the legend that the South Island — Te Waka-a-Māui — is Māui's canoe, and the top part is the front of the canoe."\n\n"So we're standing on the front of a giant canoe? A canoe that is also an island? I love Māori legends. They make geography so much more dramatic."\n\n"Next region: West Coast. Te Tai Poutini. Get ready for rain."\n\nBiscuit perked up. "How much rain?"\n\n"A LOT of rain. The West Coast is one of the wettest places in New Zealand. Some areas get over 5,000 millimetres of rain a year."\n\n"FIVE THOUSAND MILLIMETRES?!" Biscuit looked at the sunny Marlborough sky as if saying goodbye to a dear friend. "Why are we leaving the sunniest place for the RAINIEST place? That's a terrible travel plan! Who designed this route?"\n\n"You did."\n\n"...Oh. Well, I made an error. I blame sun-related overconfidence." He sighed. "Fine. Bring on the rain. But if my feathers get frizzy, I'm holding you personally responsible."\n\nAnd with that, they headed south and west, towards the wild, wet, jade-green West Coast.`,
