    famousFor: 'Pancake Rocks, jade/pounamu, rain, glaciers',
    story: `It started raining approximately four seconds after they crossed into the West Coast region.\n\n"FOUR SECONDS!" Biscuit shrieked from inside Kaia's raincoat hood, where he had taken shelter. "We were here for FOUR SECONDS before the sky attacked us!"\n\n"I warned you," Kaia said, pulling her hood up (carefully, so as not to squash Biscuit). "The West Coast — Te Tai Poutini — is famous for rain. The Southern Alps block the moisture coming in from the Tasman Sea, and it all dumps on this side. Some areas here get up to 5,000 millimetres of rain per year. That's about five times what Auckland gets."\n\n"Five TIMES?! How does anything survive here? How do people DRY their WASHING?"\n\n"They probably have dryers."\n\n"A whole region dependent on dryers. This is the apocalypse."\n\nBut here's the thing about the West Coast: all that rain creates something magical. The bush here is THICK — dense, ancient, dripping rainforest that looks like something out of a dinosaur movie. Giant tree ferns unfurl their fronds over mossy boulders. Every surface is green with growth. Waterfalls cascade down cliff faces everywhere you look. It is wild, dramatic, and absolutely stunning.\n\n"Okay," Biscuit admitted grudgingly, peering out from the hood at the rainforest. "It IS pretty. In a soggy, dripping, everything-is-wet kind of way."\n\nTheir first major stop was the Pancake Rocks at Punakaiki. These are rock formations along the coast that look exactly like — you guessed it — stacks of pancakes. Layers upon layers of limestone have been weathered over millions of years into these incredible, flat, pancake-like stacks.\n\n"THEY ACTUALLY LOOK LIKE PANCAKES!" Biscuit yelled, which Kaia felt was unnecessary given that this was literally the entire point.\n\n"They were formed about 30 million years ago," Kaia read. "Layers of limestone and softer material built up on the sea floor, and over time, wind and sea water eroded the soft layers, leaving these layered shapes."\n\nBut the REALLY spectacular part was the blowholes. When the tide is right and the swell is big, the ocean forces water up through gaps in the rocks, and massive spouts of sea water EXPLODE upward like geysers. The sound is incredible — a deep, booming WHOOOOSH followed by a shower of spray.\n\nThey were watching the blowholes when a particularly big wave hit, and a column of spray blasted up right next to the viewing platform, drenching them both.\n\n"AAAAHHH!" Biscuit screamed. "I WAS ALREADY WET! I DIDN'T NEED TO BE WETTER! IS THERE A MAXIMUM WETNESS? BECAUSE I HAVE REACHED IT!"\n\nKaia was laughing too hard to respond. She was soaked, Biscuit looked like a drowned rat (a small, round, feathery drowned rat), and the Pancake Rocks didn't care one bit. They just kept stacking there, being ancient and pancake-shaped, as the ocean boomed beneath them.\n\nFrom Punakaiki, they headed south to Greymouth — the largest town on the West Coast. Greymouth sits at the mouth of the Grey River and has a rugged, honest feel to it. The West Coast has a proud history of coal mining and gold mining, and the people here — "Coasters," as they call themselves — are famously tough, independent, and friendly.\n\n"Coasters are known for being really welcoming," Kaia said. "There's a saying on the West Coast: 'If you don't wave at every car, you're not a real Coaster.'"\n\n"I will wave at every car," Biscuit said, raising one tiny wing stub. "Starting now." He waved at a passing truck. The driver, who definitely could not see a tiny kiwi bird waving from inside a car, did not wave back.\n\n"He didn't wave back," Biscuit said, offended. "After everything I've been through. The rain. The blowholes. And now THIS."\n\nFurther south, they stopped in Hokitika, a small town that is the pounamu (greenstone/jade) capital of New Zealand. Pounamu is a precious stone that has been treasured by Māori for centuries. It's found in the rivers and mountains of the West Coast — in fact, the Māori name for the South Island's West Coast, Te Tai Poutini, comes from the taniwha (supernatural creature) who guards the pounamu.\n\n"Pounamu is incredibly significant in Māori culture," Kaia said, looking at the beautiful carved pendants in a gallery. "It's used for tools, weapons, and jewellery. A pounamu pendant — a taonga — is a treasure that carries the mana (spiritual power) of its wearers. They're often passed down through generations and become more precious over time."\n\n"So they get MORE valuable the older they get?" Biscuit said. "Unlike me, who seems to get more CREAKY the older I get."\n\nThe pendants came in different shapes — the hei-tiki (a human-like figure), the koru (an unfurling fern frond), the pikorua (a twist representing the path of life), and the hei-matau (a fish hook representing strength and safe travel over water).\n\n"I want a hei-matau," Biscuit said. "For safe travel over water. Given my history with boats, I need all the help I can get."\n\nKaia bought a small koru pendant and put it around her neck. The green stone was cool and smooth against her skin, and it felt like carrying a piece of the West Coast with her.\n\nThe West Coast is also home to two of New Zealand's most famous glaciers: Franz Josef and Fox Glacier. These massive rivers of ice flow down from the Southern Alps almost to sea level, which is incredibly rare — most glaciers in the world are at much higher altitudes.\n\n"You can actually see where the ice meets the rainforest," Kaia said, staring up at the massive wall of blue-white ice that was Franz Josef Glacier. "A glacier right next to a RAINFOREST. That's insane."\n\n"It is FREEZING here," Biscuit said, his beak chattering. "We went from rain to GLACIER. My body cannot handle these temperature changes. I am a TROPICAL bird at heart."\n\n"Kiwi birds are not tropical."\n\n"I am tropical on the INSIDE."\n\nThe glaciers were awe-inspiring — ancient, slow-moving rivers of compressed ice and snow, creaking and grinding their way down the valleys. The ice was a stunning shade of blue, caused by the way light passes through the compressed layers.\n\n"West Coast fun fact," Kaia said. "The Hokitika Gorge has water that is the most incredible turquoise colour — it looks almost fake. The colour comes from glacial flour, which is fine rock particles ground up by the glaciers. When these particles wash into the water, they scatter light and create that turquoise colour."\n\n"Glacial flour. Is that... rock flour? Can you bake with it? Can you make glacial biscuits?"\n\n"No, Biscuit. It's not that kind of flour."\n\n"This trip is full of disappointments disguised as fun facts."\n\nAs they left the West Coast, driving back over the Southern Alps, Biscuit turned for one last look at the wild, wet, green region behind them. Despite all his complaints about the rain, there had been something deeply special about the West Coast — its wildness, its ancient rainforests, its jade-green rivers, and the Pancake Rocks being absolutely drenched by blowholes.\n\n"Next stop: Canterbury," Kaia said. "Waitaha. Home to Christchurch, the Garden City, and Aoraki — Mount Cook, the tallest mountain in New Zealand."\n\n"The TALLEST mountain?" Biscuit sighed. "Kaia, I have a fear of heights. You KNOW this."\n\n"You don't have to climb it. You can just look at it."\n\n"Looking at tall things also scares me. I once got nervous looking at a tall bookshelf."\n\n"You'll be fine."\n\n"Your confidence in me is both appreciated and deeply misplaced."\n\nAnd eastward they went, leaving the rain behind and heading into the vast, flat Canterbury Plains, where the tallest mountain in Aotearoa was waiting.`,
