    story: `Canterbury — Waitaha — is the biggest region in New Zealand by area, and it feels like it. The Canterbury Plains stretch out flat and wide, a patchwork of farmland that seems to go on forever, hemmed in by the Southern Alps to the west and the Pacific Ocean to the east.\n\n"It's so FLAT," Biscuit observed from the dashboard. "After all those mountains and glaciers and gorges, it's just... flat. Like a table. I like tables. Tables are safe. Nothing falls off a table."\n\n"Things fall off tables all the time."\n\n"I choose to ignore that fact."\n\nChristchurch — Ōtautahi — is the largest city in the South Island and the capital of Canterbury. It's known as the Garden City because of its beautiful parks and gardens, especially Hagley Park and the Botanic Gardens, which are right in the heart of the city.\n\nBut Christchurch is also known for something much more sobering. In 2010 and 2011, the city was hit by devastating earthquakes. The February 2011 earthquake, a magnitude 6.3, struck at lunchtime when the city centre was full of people. It caused terrible damage — 185 people lost their lives, and much of the central city was destroyed.\n\n"This is really sad," Biscuit said quietly as they walked through the city and saw the ongoing rebuild.\n\n"It is," Kaia agreed. "But Christchurch didn't give up. The city has been rebuilding itself, and what's amazing is HOW they're rebuilding. They're using the opportunity to create something new and innovative."\n\nAnd it was true. The new Christchurch was like no other city in New Zealand. Alongside restored heritage buildings, there were new, earthquake-resistant structures with bold, modern designs. There were pop-up shops in shipping containers. There was street art everywhere — murals covering the sides of buildings, turning the city into an open-air gallery.\n\n"Look at this!" Kaia said, staring at a massive mural of a blue whale painted across an entire wall. "The art scene here is incredible."\n\n"If this city can survive earthquakes and come back with THIS much creativity," Biscuit said, "then I can survive getting drenched at the Pancake Rocks. It's about perspective."\n\n"That might be the wisest thing you've ever said."\n\n"Don't get used to it. I'll say something stupid soon, I promise."\n\nOne of the most striking symbols of Christchurch's resilience is the Cardboard Cathedral — a temporary cathedral designed by a famous Japanese architect, built using cardboard tubes, shipping containers, and timber. It was erected after the original Christchurch Cathedral was badly damaged in the earthquake, and it's a beautiful, light-filled space that proves you don't need stone and marble to create something sacred.\n\n"A cathedral made of CARDBOARD?!" Biscuit was amazed. "That's either genius or madness."\n\n"It's genius. The cardboard tubes are coated and treated so they're waterproof and fire-resistant. It can hold 700 people."\n\n"Engineers are WIZARDS, Kaia. That's my conclusion. Wizards."\n\nThey punted on the Avon River — a gentle, winding river that flows through the centre of the city. Punting involves standing on a flat-bottomed boat and pushing along with a long pole, and it's one of Christchurch's most famous experiences. Weeping willows drape over the banks, ducks paddle alongside, and it's incredibly peaceful.\n\nBiscuit, of course, sat in the punt looking nervous.\n\n"The water is RIGHT THERE," he said, peering over the edge. "I could fall in at any moment."\n\n"The Avon River is about knee-deep here. You'd be fine."\n\n"YOUR knee-deep is MY entire-body-deep! I would be SUBMERGED!"\n\nFrom Christchurch, they drove south through the Canterbury Plains, passing Timaru, a pleasant coastal city about halfway to Dunedin. Then they turned inland, heading west towards the mountains.\n\nAnd then they saw it. Aoraki. Mount Cook.\n\nAt 3,724 metres, Aoraki/Mount Cook is the tallest mountain in New Zealand. It rose above the other peaks like a king on a throne, its summit sharp and white with permanent snow and ice, its flanks scarred with glaciers.\n\nKaia actually stopped breathing for a second.\n\n"Oh," she said. "Oh wow."\n\nBiscuit looked up. And up. And up. His beak fell open.\n\n"That's the tallest thing I have ever seen," he whispered. "That is taller than the Sky Tower. That is taller than EVERYTHING. That is nature showing off."\n\nThe Māori name Aoraki comes from a creation story. Aoraki was one of the sons of Rakinui (the Sky Father), whose canoe was tipped by a wave and turned to stone, becoming the South Island. Aoraki and his brothers climbed to the highest point and were turned to stone by the cold south wind, becoming the highest peaks of the Southern Alps.\n\n"Turned to stone by WIND?" Biscuit shivered. "Note to self: avoid cold south winds. I already don't trust wind."\n\nThey walked the Hooker Valley Track, a stunning trail that leads to a glacial lake at the base of Aoraki. Swing bridges crossed milky, glacial rivers. Icebergs floated in the lake. The mountain towered above them, constantly changing as clouds moved across its peak.\n\n"There are actual ICEBERGS in this lake," Kaia said. "We're looking at chunks of ice that broke off a glacier."\n\n"I am touching an iceberg," Biscuit said, reaching out a tentative foot to a chunk of ice at the lake's edge. "OW! It's COLD!"\n\n"It's ICE, Biscuit. What did you THINK it would be?"\n\n"I thought it might be friendly ice! Warm ice! Welcoming ice!"\n\n"That's called WATER."\n\n"Don't get scientific with me, I'm having a MOMENT."\n\nThe Aoraki/Mount Cook region is also home to the largest glacier in New Zealand — the Tasman Glacier, which is 23 kilometres long. And because the area is so remote and high up, it's been designated a Dark Sky Reserve, meaning on clear nights, the stargazing is absolutely out of this world.\n\n"Canterbury fun fact," Kaia said. "Sir Edmund Hillary, the first person to climb Mount Everest, trained on the mountains around Aoraki. He used to say the mountains of Canterbury were where he learned to climb."\n\n"So the first human to stand on top of the world practised HERE?" Biscuit looked at the mountains with new respect. "These peaks are the training ground of LEGENDS."\n\n"That's genuinely poetic, Biscuit."\n\n"I have layers. Like the Pancake Rocks. But drier."\n\nAs they headed south towards Otago, Kaia looked back at Aoraki one last time. The mountain was glowing pink in the sunset, its ice catching the last light like a crown.\n\n"Next up: Otago," she said. "Ōtākou. Home to Queenstown, Dunedin, the steepest street in the world, and more adventure sports than you can imagine."\n\n"Adventure sports?" Biscuit said nervously. "Like what?"\n\n"Bungee jumping. Skydiving. Jet boating. Zorbing—"\n\n"NONE of those words are okay, Kaia. Not a SINGLE one. I am a kiwi bird who is scared of heights, scared of water, and scared of being inside a giant ball. That covers ALL of those activities."\n\n"It's going to be fun."\n\n"Fun for WHO?"\n\n"Both of us."\n\n"DEBATABLE!"\n\nBut onward they went, south towards the adventure capital of the world.`,
