    story: `Otago — Ōtākou — is a region that can't seem to decide if it wants to be Scotland or an adrenaline junkie's paradise. It's somehow both.\n\n"Why does Dunedin look like Edinburgh?" Biscuit asked as they drove into Otago's largest city. And he wasn't wrong. Dunedin has a distinctly Scottish feel — grand stone buildings, a cathedral, a statue of the poet Robbie Burns, and street names like Princes Street and George Street.\n\n"Dunedin was founded by Scottish settlers in 1848," Kaia explained. "The name 'Dunedin' actually comes from Dùn Èideann, which is the Scottish Gaelic name for Edinburgh. The settlers basically tried to recreate Scotland in the South Island."\n\n"Did they bring the rain too?"\n\n"Dunedin does get a fair bit of rain, yes."\n\n"Authentically Scottish. Full marks."\n\nDunedin had a massive boom during the 1860s gold rush, when gold was discovered in Central Otago. For a while, it was the richest and most important city in New Zealand. You can still see that wealth in the gorgeous old buildings — the Dunedin Railway Station is one of the most photographed buildings in the country, with its ornate stone facade, stained glass windows, and mosaic floor with over 725,000 tiles.\n\n"Seven hundred and twenty-five thousand tiles?!" Biscuit counted on his... actually, kiwi birds don't have fingers. He tried counting on his toes. He has three. "That's a LOT of tiles. Imagine being the person who had to lay tile number 725,000. 'Just one more, mate. Just ONE more.'"\n\nBut the thing Biscuit was most nervous about — and most excited about — was Baldwin Street. Baldwin Street in Dunedin is the steepest residential street in the world. It rises at a gradient of 34.8 percent, which means for every 2.86 metres you walk forward, you go up one metre.\n\n"It doesn't LOOK that steep from down here," Biscuit said, standing at the bottom.\n\nThen they started walking up.\n\n"OKAY IT IS THAT STEEP," Biscuit gasped approximately four steps in. "My legs! MY TINY LEGS! They were not designed for THIS! I am not a mountain goat! I am a KIWI BIRD! We live on FLAT GROUND!"\n\nKaia was also struggling — her calves burned and she had to lean forward like she was climbing a ladder. But they made it to the top, panting and triumphant.\n\n"I climbed the steepest street in the world," Biscuit wheezed, lying flat on the pavement at the top. "Put that on my tombstone. 'Here lies Biscuit. He climbed the thing.'"\n\nFrom Dunedin, they headed inland to Queenstown — and everything changed. If Dunedin is dignified and Scottish, Queenstown is its wild younger sibling who thinks rules are suggestions.\n\nQueenstown is the adventure capital of the world. Seriously. The town sits on the shores of Lake Wakatipu, surrounded by the Remarkables mountain range (which is indeed remarkable), and every possible adrenaline activity known to humanity is available here.\n\n"Bungee jumping was basically INVENTED here," Kaia said excitedly. "AJ Hackett jumped off the Kawarau Bridge in 1988, and it became the world's first commercial bungee jump."\n\nBiscuit looked at the Kawarau Bridge. Then at the gorge below. Then at Kaia. Then back at the gorge.\n\n"Absolutely not," he said.\n\n"I wasn't suggesting YOU bungee jump."\n\n"Good. Because I would rather eat my own feathers. I would rather be hit by a wave again. I would rather go BACK to the surfing incident than jump off that bridge."\n\nThey watched other people bungee jump instead, and Biscuit provided colourful commentary. "She's going to jump— SHE JUMPED! WHY WOULD ANYONE— oh, she's bouncing, she's fine, she's laughing, WHAT IS WRONG WITH HUMANS?"\n\nQueenstown also offers jet boating (speeding through narrow river canyons at terrifying speeds), skydiving (jumping out of a perfectly good aeroplane), and zip-lining (sliding along a cable above a canyon). Kaia was too young for most of these, but she loved the energy of the town.\n\n"Even just WATCHING people do these things is giving me a heart attack," Biscuit said, clutching his chest. "My heart is the size of a grape and it is WORKING OVERTIME."\n\nLake Wakatipu itself was stunning — a long, lightning-bolt-shaped lake surrounded by mountains. According to Māori legend, the lake was formed by the burning of a giant sleeping demon. The lake's water level rises and falls slightly every few minutes, which is said to be the demon's heartbeat still pulsing.\n\n"The lake has a HEARTBEAT?!" Biscuit stared at the water. "From a DEMON?! I'm never going near water again. EVER."\n\n"It's actually caused by a natural phenomenon called a seiche — a standing wave in the lake caused by atmospheric pressure. But the demon legend is better."\n\n"I'm going with the demon explanation. It's more honest about how TERRIFYING lakes are."\n\nThey also visited Wanaka, a gorgeous lakeside town about an hour from Queenstown. Wanaka is slightly quieter and more relaxed, sitting on the edge of its own beautiful lake with views of Mount Aspiring. The famous Wanaka Tree — a lone willow tree growing in the lake — is one of the most photographed trees in New Zealand.\n\n"That tree is living IN the water," Biscuit said. "In the LAKE. A tree. Growing in a lake. That tree is braver than me. A PLANT is braver than me. I need to reevaluate my life."\n\n"You climbed Baldwin Street today. Give yourself some credit."\n\n"You're right. I climbed the steepest street in the world AND I didn't bungee jump. Two achievements. One of effort and one of excellent judgement."\n\nOtago is also home to some incredible wildlife. On the Otago Peninsula near Dunedin, you can see yellow-eyed penguins (one of the rarest penguins in the world), royal albatrosses (enormous seabirds with wingspans over three metres), and New Zealand fur seals.\n\n"An albatross has a three-metre wingspan?" Biscuit looked at his own tiny wing stubs. "THREE METRES? That bird could use me as a BOOKMARK. I am officially the least impressive bird in this region."\n\n"You're the only one that can talk."\n\n"...That IS a good point. Okay, I'm the most TALENTED bird. Just the least aerodynamic."\n\n"Otago fun fact," Kaia said. "During the gold rush in the 1860s, thousands of people flooded into Central Otago looking for gold. The population of Dunedin exploded, and it became the biggest, richest city in the country. You can still visit old gold mining towns like Arrowtown, where the old miners' cottages are still standing."\n\n"Gold rush!" Biscuit said. "I'd have been terrible at gold mining. Short arms. Can't hold a shovel. Can't pan for gold because pans are bigger than me. But I COULD have been the mascot. Every mining camp needs a mascot."\n\nAs the sun set over the Remarkables (the mountains turning from grey to orange to purple in the fading light), Kaia felt a twinge of sadness. There was only one region left. Their journey was almost over.\n\n"Last stop," she said quietly. "Southland. Murihiku. The bottom of the South Island."\n\n"The very end," Biscuit said, and for once, he didn't make a joke. He just looked at the mountains and the lake and the impossibly beautiful Otago landscape, and let himself feel grateful.\n\nThen: "Do they have snacks in Southland?"\n\n"Biscuit."\n\n"What? I can be emotional AND hungry. They're not mutually exclusive."\n\nAnd so, for the last time, they hit the road — heading south to the very bottom of Aotearoa.`,
