    story: `Southland — Murihiku, which means "the tail end of the land" — is where New Zealand runs out of land and becomes ocean. It's the southernmost region in the country, wild and remote and full of wonders that made Kaia feel like she'd reached the edge of the world.\n\nBecause, in a way, she had.\n\n"We're at the BOTTOM," Biscuit said, looking at the map. "The very, very bottom. After this, it's just Antarctica."\n\n"There's a lot of ocean between here and Antarctica."\n\n"But EVENTUALLY it's Antarctica. With penguins. Real penguins. Not me. I look like a penguin but I am NOT a penguin. We've been over this."\n\nTheir first stop was Invercargill, Southland's main city and the southernmost city in New Zealand. Invercargill has wide, flat streets (originally designed wide enough to turn a bullock cart around), a friendly, down-to-earth vibe, and some surprisingly cool things hiding in it.\n\n"Invercargill is home to the Burt Munro Challenge," Kaia read. "Burt Munro was a local legend — a motorcycle racer who rebuilt an old Indian motorcycle in his backyard shed and then took it to the Bonneville Salt Flats in the United States, where he broke the world speed record. He was nearly seventy years old at the time!"\n\n"An old man from Invercargill broke a WORLD SPEED RECORD on a motorbike he built in his SHED?!" Biscuit's beak dropped open. "That is the most New Zealand thing I have ever heard. Just quietly building something amazing in your shed and then shocking the world."\n\n"They made a movie about him — The World's Fastest Indian, with Anthony Hopkins."\n\n"I would watch that movie. I love a good shed-to-glory story."\n\nFrom Invercargill, they drove to Te Anau, the gateway town to Fiordland National Park. Te Anau sits on the edge of Lake Te Anau, the largest lake in the South Island, and the whole area feels EPIC — enormous mountains, dense beech forests, and a sense of remoteness that makes you feel very small.\n\n"Fiordland is one of the wettest places on Earth," Kaia said. "Even wetter than the West Coast. It gets about 8,000 millimetres of rain in some areas."\n\n"EIGHT THOUSAND?!" Biscuit yelped. "That's not a weather pattern, that's a LIFESTYLE CHOICE by clouds!"\n\nBut all that rain was worth it for what came next: Milford Sound. Or, more accurately, Piopiotahi.\n\nMilford Sound is a fiord — a long, narrow inlet carved by glaciers, surrounded by sheer cliff faces that rise straight up from the dark water like the walls of a cathedral. Waterfalls plunge from hundreds of metres above, crashing into the sea in misty curtains. Mitre Peak, the iconic mountain at the head of the fiord, towers 1,692 metres above the water.\n\nWhen their boat turned a corner and Milford Sound opened up before them, Kaia felt her eyes fill with tears. It was, without question, the most breathtaking thing she had ever seen.\n\n"I have no words," she whispered.\n\nBiscuit, for the first time in the entire trip, was completely silent. He stood on the deck of the boat, looking up at the impossible walls of rock and water, and said nothing. Not a joke. Not a complaint. Nothing.\n\nAfter a full minute, he said, very quietly: "This is what the world looked like before people. This is how it was always meant to be."\n\nKaia nodded. She couldn't speak.\n\nThey sailed through the fiord in awed silence, passing waterfalls that were taller than skyscrapers, watching seals bask on rocks, and spotting a pod of bottlenose dolphins playing in the wake of the boat. The captain sailed close to Stirling Falls, and the spray misted over them like gentle rain.\n\n"I'm on a boat and I'm not even scared," Biscuit realised. "This place is so beautiful it cured my seasickness. Milford Sound is MEDICINE."\n\nRudyard Kipling, the famous writer, once called Milford Sound the "eighth wonder of the world." Standing there, surrounded by millions of years of geological history, Kaia understood why.\n\nAfter Milford Sound, they made one more stop — Stewart Island, or Rakiura, which lies across Foveaux Strait from the very bottom of the South Island. Stewart Island is New Zealand's third-largest island, but only about 400 people live there. It's covered in native bush, circled by wild beaches, and is one of the best places in the country to see kiwi birds in the wild.\n\n"MY PEOPLE!" Biscuit shouted as they arrived on the island. "Kiwi birds! REAL kiwi birds! In the WILD! This is my homeland! This is my ROOTS!"\n\n"Have you ever actually been here before?"\n\n"No. But it's SPIRITUALLY my homeland. I can feel it in my bones. Which are hollow, because I'm a bird, so I can feel a LOT through them."\n\nThat evening, a guide took them on a kiwi-spotting walk on Ocean Beach. In the dim twilight, they crept along the beach in silence, and there — emerging from the bush onto the sand — was a wild kiwi bird. A real, wild, Southern brown kiwi, pecking at the sand with its long beak, searching for insects.\n\nBiscuit watched with enormous eyes. The wild kiwi was about the same size as him, with the same round body, the same long beak, the same tiny wing stubs.\n\n"That's me," he breathed. "That's... that's what I am. Out here, in the wild. Where we started. Before everything."\n\nKaia felt a lump in her throat. She put her hand gently on Biscuit's back.\n\n"You're pretty amazing, you know that?" she said.\n\n"Yeah," Biscuit said, and his voice cracked. "Yeah, I know." He sniffed. "Emotional wind again. Very strong on this island."\n\nStewart Island had one more surprise. Because it's so far south and so free from light pollution, it's one of the best places in New Zealand to see the Southern Lights — Aurora Australis. That night, the sky erupted in waves of green and pink light, rippling across the stars like curtains of colour.\n\n"The Southern Lights," Kaia breathed, lying on her back on the beach, staring up at the sky. "I never thought I'd actually see them."\n\n"Kaia," Biscuit said.\n\n"Yeah?"\n\n"Thank you. For this trip. For all of it. For every region, every volcano, every terrible boat ride, every cave, every glacier, every rotten-egg-smelling geothermal pool. Thank you for doing this with me."\n\nKaia smiled. "Thank you for convincing me to go. I've learned more in this trip than I have in years of school. And I laughed more than I've ever laughed in my life."\n\n"That's because I'm hilarious."\n\n"You ARE hilarious." She paused. "Don't let it go to your head."\n\n"Too late. It's already there. My head is 90 percent ego now." Biscuit shuffled closer to her and they both watched the aurora dance across the southern sky.\n\nSixteen regions. From Cape Reinga to Stewart Island. From ancient kauri forests to underground glowworms, from volcanic plateaus to golden beaches, from Art Deco cities to glacier-carved fiords. They'd seen it all — every corner, every coast, every mountain and river and wild, wonderful place in Aotearoa New Zealand.\n\n"Southland fun fact," Kaia murmured, sleepy and happy. "The name Murihiku means 'the tail end of the land.' But you know what? It doesn't feel like an ending. It feels like we've just found the beginning."\n\n"The beginning of what?" Biscuit asked.\n\n"Of knowing this place. Really knowing it. And wanting to come back to every single region and explore more."\n\n"Agreed. Starting with wherever has the best snacks."\n\nKaia laughed. Above them, the Southern Lights painted the sky in green and gold, and the stars of the southern hemisphere blazed bright and fierce, and somewhere in the bush behind them, a wild kiwi bird called out into the night.\n\nIt sounded, Kaia thought, exactly like Biscuit.\n\nIt sounded like home.`,
